title: Exploration using dataframes
text: using NOAA dataset used book Spatio-Temporal Statistics R Christopher K. Wikle, Andrew Zammit-Mangion Noel Cressie. dataset ’re using contains precipitation, maximum minimum temperatures years 1990 1993 regions United States. Let’s look dataset.

title: Exploration using dataframes
text: First ’re going explore dataset using simple methods.

title: Exploration using dataframes
text: focus maximum temperature see changes time 1993. First filter data Tmax year 1993 months 5 9. field julian unique number day. make new column represent days starting 1 select certain days. Now can use spatial_snapshots function. function need give data frame columns used latitude, longitude, time column quantity want plot. can also give main legend title plot.  Suppose want plot maximum temperature days 1 12.
code: Tmax <- filter(NOAA_df_1990,   proc == "Tmax" &   month %in% 5:9 &   year == 1993) Tmax$t <- Tmax$julian - min(Tmax$julian) + 1 Tmax_days <- subset(Tmax, t %in% c(1, 15, 30)) spatial_snapshots(Tmax_days,           lat_col = 'lat',           lon_col = 'lon',           t_col = 't',           z_col = 'z',            title = "Maximum Temperature for 3 days",          legend_title = 'Temp') Tmax_days <- subset(Tmax, t %in% c(1:12))  spatial_snapshots(Tmax_days,           lat_col = 'lat',           lon_col = 'lon',           t_col = 't',           z_col = 'z',            title = "Maximum Temperature for 12 days",          legend_title = 'Temp')

what: Time series snapshots for different locations
title: Exploration using dataframes
text: looked spatial snapshots time. Now let’s look temporal snapshots given spatial locations. First let’s look location ids sample 12 . use temporal_snapshots function plot temporal snapshots locations. Similar previous function, need specify dataframe, time column, value column, id column id samples. can specify x y labels title.
code: set.seed(148)                                           Tmax_ID <- unique(Tmax$id)                                ids <- sample(Tmax_ID, 12) ids #>  [1] 14926 93842 14848 93820  3919 94918 13871 94823 13988  3952 13971  3841 temporal_snapshots(Tmax,           t_col = 't',           z_col = 'z',           id_col = 'id',           id_sample = ids,            xlab = "Days",           ylab="Temperature",          title = "Temperature Selected Days")

title: Exploration using dataframes
text: Hovmollet plots generally used reduce spatial dimensions. sometimes called cross map graph. commmonly used collapse one spatial dimensions. example maximum temperature different latitude, longitude time values. can average latitude see maximum temperature changes time longitude. can average longitude explore changes maximum temperature respect latitude time. function hovmoller takes similar arguments functions exception lat_or_lon lat_or_lon_col arguments. argument lat_or_lon specifies, spatial component see plot. specify lat, see plot quantity interest (Max Temp case) latitude time two axes. specify lon, see longitude x-axis. argument lat_or_lon_col used specify column corresponding spatial variable. average longitude, need specify lat_or_lon = ‘lat’. , want see latitude x-axis, specify lat.  graph gives valuable information. see higher latitudes maximum temperature low compared lower latitudes. another interesting bit information. dataset Tmax spans 150 days May September. Spring Autumn Northern Hemisphere. Generally, maximum daily temperature go May July/August go . confirmed parabolic pattern dark red/orange squares see time. want see longitude x-axis (average latitude), need specify lat_or_lon = ‘lon’. plot interesting.
code: hov <- hovmoller(lat_or_lon = "lat",                  x = Tmax,                  lat_or_lon_col = 'lat',                  t_col = 't',                  z_col = 'z') autoplot(hov, legend_title = "Temperature") hov <- hovmoller (lat_or_lon = "lon",                   x = Tmax,                   lat_or_lon_col = 'lon',                   t_col = 't',                   z_col = 'z') autoplot(hov, legend_title = "Temperature")

title: Exploration using dataframes
text: explore empirical covariances, first remove trends examine residuals. emp_spatial_cov function can remove either linear quadratic trends space time. set quadratic_time = TRUE quadratic trend removed time. Similarly set quadratic_space = TRUE, quadratic component space removed. arguments set FALSE linear trend removed. emp_spatial_cov function can plot latitude longitude strips empirical covariance. , can divide spatial domain strips corresponding either latitude longitude plot associated covariance matrices strips. Let’s see longitudinal strips dataset removing quadratic time linear space trend. see change latitude values.  Similarly, can also plot latitude strips; x axis longitude .  can also compute lagged covariance. setting lag parameter. Let’s see lagged-1 empirical covariance data removing quadratic trend time.
code: esv <- emp_spatial_cov(Tmax,                        lat_col = "lat",                        lon_col = "lon",                        t_col ="t",                        z_col = "z",                        num_strips = 4,                        quadratic_space = FALSE,                        quadratic_time = TRUE,                        lat_or_lon_strips = "lon" )  autoplot(esv) esv <- emp_spatial_cov(Tmax,                        lat_col = "lat",                        lon_col = "lon",                        t_col ="t",                        z_col = "z",                        num_strips = 4,                        quadratic_space = FALSE,                        quadratic_time = TRUE,                        lat_or_lon_strips = "lat" ) autoplot(esv) # longitudinal strips esv1 <- emp_spatial_cov(Tmax,                         lat_col = "lat",                         lon_col = "lon",                         t_col ="t",                         z_col = "z",                         num_strips = 4,                         quadratic_space = FALSE,                         quadratic_time = TRUE,                         lat_or_lon_strips = "lon",                         lag = 1 ) autoplot(esv1) # latitude strips esv2 <- emp_spatial_cov(Tmax,                         lat_col = "lat",                         lon_col = "lon",                         t_col ="t",                         z_col = "z",                         num_strips = 4,                         quadratic_space = FALSE,                         quadratic_time = TRUE,                         lat_or_lon_strips = "lat",                         lag = 1 ) autoplot(esv2)

text: plot space-time semi-variograms need construct object STDF Class. inside function semivariogram. create STDF object, need spatio-temporal data full spate-time grid. , need matrix M x N size, N number spatial locations M number timestamps. code: # Location data data(locs) head(locs) #>     id      lat       lon #> 1 3804 39.35000 -81.43333 #> 2 3809 36.01667 -89.40000 #> 3 3810 35.73333 -81.38333 #> 4 3811 35.60000 -88.91666 #> 5 3812 35.43333 -82.48333 #> 6 3813 32.70000 -83.65000 dim(locs) #> [1] 328   3  # Timestamp data data(Times) head(Times) #>   julian year month day #> 1 726834 1990     1   1 #> 2 726835 1990     1   2 #> 3 726836 1990     1   3 #> 4 726837 1990     1   4 #> 5 726838 1990     1   5 #> 6 726839 1990     1   6 dim(Times) #> [1] 1461    4  # Spatio-temporal data data(Tmax) dim(Tmax)  #> [1] 1461  328 temp_part <- with(Times, paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")) # Selecting the dates from 0992-07-01 to 1992-07-31 temp_part <- data.frame(date = as.Date(temp_part)[913:943]) Tmax2 <- Tmax[913:943, ] semiv <- semivariogram(locs,         temp_part,         Tmax2,         latitude_linear = FALSE,         longitude_linear = FALSE,         missing_value = -9999,         width = 50,         cutoff = 1000,         tlagmax = 7 ) autoplot(semiv) semiv<- semivariogram(locs,         temp_part,         Tmax2,         latitude_linear = TRUE,         longitude_linear = FALSE,         missing_value = -9999,         width = 50,         cutoff = 1000,         tlagmax = 7) autoplot(semiv) semiv <- semivariogram(locs,         temp_part,         Tmax2,         latitude_linear = TRUE,         longitude_linear = TRUE,         missing_value = -9999,         width = 50,         cutoff = 1000,         tlagmax = 7) autoplot(semiv)

title: Exploration using dataframes
text: Empirical orthogonal functions PCA equivalent spatio-temporal data. \[Z(x,y,t) = \sum_{k = 1}^N \lambda_k PC_k(t) \times EOF_k(x,y)\] multiplication denotes outer product. value \(PC_k(t)\), \(EOF_k(x,y)\) gets multiplied get 3D data cube. adding \(N\) data cubes get \(Z\) back.  first EOF PC time series. Let’s look second EOF associated time series.  EOF used dimension reduction tool. matrix shows correlation first 3 PC time series. diagonal elements close zero. Just like PCA, PC time series uncorrelated.
code: data(SSTlonlatshort) data(SSTdatashort) data(SSTlandmaskshort) # Take first 396 months (33 years) and delete land delete_rows <- which(SSTlandmaskshort  ==  1) SSTdatashort   <- SSTdatashort[-delete_rows, 1:396] eoff <- emp_orth_fun(SSTlonlatshort[-delete_rows,  ],                      SSTdatashort) autoplot(eoff) autoplot(eoff, EOF_num = 2) pcs <- eoff$pcts %>%    select(t, EOF, nPC) %>%    pivot_wider(names_from = EOF, values_from = nPC) %>%   select(-t)  cormat <- cor(pcs)[1:3, 1:3] cormat #>               X1            X2            X3 #> X1  1.000000e+00  1.306506e-17 -3.208918e-17 #> X2  1.306506e-17  1.000000e+00 -6.372879e-18 #> X3 -3.208918e-17 -6.372879e-18  1.000000e+00

title: Exploration using dataframes
text: Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA) used identify associations two sets variables. example suppose \(X_1, X_2, X_3\) variables psychological survey set participants. Let \(Y_1, Y_2, Y_3, Y_4\) set university grades set participants. CCA finds new variables maximizes correlation X Y sets variables. example CCA finds \(U_1 = a_1 X_1 + a_2 X_2 + a_3 X_3\) \(V_1 = b_1 Y_1 + b_2 Y_2 + b_3 Y_3 + b_4 Y_4\) correlation \(U_1\) \(V_1\) maximized. Similarly, finds \(U_2\) \(V_2\) . spatio-temporal setting can either use two different datasets can use lagged version dataset. , implement CCA raw data datasets unique time points \(T < n\) \(n\) gives number spatial points. carry CCA Empirical Orthogonal Functions data. Recall EOFs find temporal PC vectors spatial EOF maps. \[Z(x,y,t) = \sum_{k = 1}^N \lambda_k PC_k(t) \times EOF_k(x,y)\] take number temporal PCs compute CCA . can two ways. ’re interested future predictions data, can use lagged dataset. case, first dataset \(PC_k(t)\) \(1 \leq t \leq (T - \ell)\) \(k\) \(l\) denotes lag, second dataset \(PC_k(t)\) \((\ell +1) \leq t \leq T\) \(k\). analysis give us new variables. plot first new temporal variable first dataset first new temporal variable second dataset.  can also produce weighted maps. can weight EOF maps \(EOF_k(x,y)\) CCA coefficients. map weighted map.

title: Computes the semi-variogram using a dataframe or a stars object. — semivariogram
code: # Dataframe example library(dplyr) data(locs) data(Times) data(Tmax) temp_part <- with(Times, paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")) temp_part <- data.frame(date = as.Date(temp_part)[913:923]) Tmax <- Tmax[913:923, ] semidf <- semivariogram(locs,         temp_part,         Tmax,         latitude_linear = FALSE,         longitude_linear = FALSE,         missing_value = -9999,         width = 50,         cutoff = 1000,         tlagmax = 7 ) autoplot(semidf)   # Stars example library(stars) # Create a stars object from a data frame precip_df <- NOAA_df_1990[NOAA_df_1990$proc == 'Precip', ] %>%   filter(date >= "1992-02-01" & date <= "1992-02-05") precip <- precip_df[ ,c('lat', 'lon', 'date', 'z')] st_precip <- st_as_stars(precip, dims = c("lon", "lat", "date")) semist <- semivariogram(st_precip) autoplot(semist)

title: Computes spatial empirical means using a dataframe or a stars object — spatial_means
code: # dataframe example data(NOAA_df_1990) library(dplyr) Tmax <- filter(NOAA_df_1990,                      # subset the data               proc == "Tmax" &                   # extract max temperature                 month %in% 5:9 &                 # May to July                 year == 1993)                    # year 1993 Tmax$t <- Tmax$julian - min(Tmax$julian) + 1      # create a new time variable starting at 1 sp_df <- spatial_means(Tmax,        lat_col = "lat",        lon_col = "lon",        t_col = "t",        z_col = "z") autoplot(sp_df)  #> TableGrob (2 x 2) "arrange": 3 grobs #>   z     cells    name                 grob #> 1 1 (2-2,1-1) arrange       gtable[layout] #> 2 2 (2-2,2-2) arrange       gtable[layout] #> 3 3 (1-1,1-2) arrange text[GRID.text.1127]  # stars examples library(stars) tif = system.file("tif/olinda_dem_utm25s.tif", package = "stars") x <- read_stars(tif) sp_means <- spatial_means(x) #> Only one observation of each location is present. The mean is the original value itself! autoplot(sp_means)  #> TableGrob (3 x 2) "arrange": 4 grobs #>   z     cells    name                 grob #> 1 1 (2-2,1-1) arrange       gtable[layout] #> 2 2 (2-2,2-2) arrange       gtable[layout] #> 3 3 (3-3,1-2) arrange       gtable[layout] #> 4 4 (1-1,1-2) arrange text[GRID.text.1251]

code: library(dplyr) # Dataframe example data(NOAA_df_1990) Tmax <- filter(NOAA_df_1990,   proc == "Tmax" &   month == 5 &   year == 1993 &   id < 4000) Tmax$t <- Tmax$julian - min(Tmax$julian) + 1 Tmax_days <- subset(Tmax, t %in% c(1, 15)) spatial_snapshots(Tmax_days,   lat_col = 'lat',   lon_col = 'lon',   t_col = 't',   z_col = 'z',   title = "Maximum Temperature for 2 days ")   # stars example library(stars) tif = system.file("tif/L7_ETMs.tif", package = "stars") x <- read_stars(tif) x2 <- x %>% slice(band, 1:2) spatial_snapshots(x2)

title: Plots temporal snapshots of data for specific spatial locations using a dataframe or a stars object. — temporal_snapshots
code: # Dataframe example library(dplyr) data(NOAA_df_1990) Tmax <- filter(NOAA_df_1990,              proc == "Tmax" &              month %in% 5:9 &              year == 1993) Tmax_ID <- unique(Tmax$id) Tmax$t <- Tmax$julian - min(Tmax$julian) + 1 ids <- sample(Tmax_ID, 10) temporal_snapshots(Tmax,                   t_col = 't',                   z_col = 'z',                   id_col = 'id',                   id_sample = ids)    # stars example library(stars) tif = system.file("tif/L7_ETMs.tif", package = "stars") x <- read_stars(tif) xvals <- c(288876.0,289047.0) yvals <- c(9120405, 9120006) temporal_snapshots(x,                   xvals = xvals,                   yvals = yvals)
